{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"body":"DERISKING EXPERIMENTS (2026-07-09) — results that validate the plan of record.\n\n## 1. Recall (the load-bearing bet): does lexical BM25F over LLM Cupid-digests catch paraphrase WITHOUT embeddings?\nMethod: 8 seed tickets → heavy LLM paraphrases (minimal literal overlap) as queries; every ticket Cupid-enriched (JSON {problem_keywords, component_or_area, key_entities, propositions}); field-weighted BM25F over digests vs raw-BM25 baseline; measured at 60- and 200-ticket corpora.\nResult:\n- digest-BM25F: recall@10 = recall@20 = 1.0, MRR = 1.0 at BOTH scales (8/8 seeds at rank 1).\n- raw-BM25 baseline: recall@20 0.875 (60) → 0.75 (200) — DEGRADES as distractors grow; digest holds perfect.\n- Example: paraphrase \"multiple independent signatures on same object being overwritten instead of accumulated\" → digest rank 1, raw rank 49.\nVERDICT: no-embeddings design is justified for RECALL at few-hundred scale. Caveats: N=8 (95% CI lower bound ~0.63 → \"≥0.8 demonstrated\", not \"1.0 guaranteed\"; a 30–50-query eval would tighten it). The residual risk is PRECISION at scale (query+doc digests share a model → vocab converges → near-dups converge too) — owned by S6's pairwise judge. If precision later bites, add a cheap re-rank, NOT an embedding index.\n\n## 2. Latency: brute-force vs ANN.\nBM25F single-query top-20, naive pure-Python: 0.17 ms @ 300 digests, 0.69 ms @ 800 (~14× under the 10 ms budget). VERDICT: brute-force is correct; no ANN / vector DB at this scale.\n\n## 3. Enrichment economics.\nMeasured (Haiku 4.5): 727 in + 336 out tokens/ticket, ~3.4 s serial, $0.0024/ticket. Full store (793 tickets) ≈ $1.90 one-time, cached, re-run only on edit. VERDICT: amortized enrichment is cheap; shared-store cache pays for itself.\n\n## 4. Store-primitive confirmations (code inspection).\n- Manual write-lock `lock.acquire`/`LockHandle` + `txn.py::_acquire_write_lock` run ONE critical section across multiple appends → the queue's read-check-append claim AND atomic cert+enqueue are both achievable (S3 corrected: atomicity is possible, not impossible as an earlier draft claimed).\n- `_engine_support/gates.py::_ticket_text` IS the canonical title+desc+comments normalizer → S2 reuses it for content-hash (drops the reinvented normalization that would have mis-hashed).\n- Windows detach constants `DETACHED_PROCESS`/`CREATE_NO_WINDOW` are Windows-only (absent on POSIX) → S4 references them only inside an `os.name==\"nt\"` branch. API-derisked; not live-tested (no Windows host).\n\nExperiment scripts/caches live under /tmp/cupid_exp/ (recall) and inline (latency); no repo files touched.\n"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1783623183019628001,"uuid":"baac7d1f-9224-4598-842f-41deb49c6ff9"}